    <div class="blog-body">
        <h2>Understanding Time Logic</h2>
        <p>Time calculation is the one numerical system that most frequently shatters basic arithmetic. Why? Because while our standard math utilizes a Base-10 system cleanly rolling over at 100, the clock strictly utilizes a Base-60 system. Knowing exactly how to calculate time duration is a critical necessity for shift managers scheduling payroll, freelancers invoicing clients, athletes tracking splits, and travelers managing layovers across disparate time zones.</p>
        
        <p>In this detailed process guide, we will unpack how to execute exact Base-60 subtraction mentally. We will review step-by-step procedures for cross-AM/PM durations, map a real-world scenario outlining the "borrowing" technique necessary for minutes, and link out to automated tool hubs designed to crunch massive multi-employee timesheets instantaneously.</p>

        <h2>The Standard Time Formula</h2>
        <p>At its core, calculating elapsed time is a subtraction problem. You must always mathematically subtract the smaller starting timestamp from the larger ending timestamp. The complexity occurs purely when the subtraction demands borrowing minutes from the hours column.</p>
        
        <div class="formula-box">
            <strong>Duration Formula:</strong><br><br>
            <code>Elapsed Time = End Time - Start Time</code>
        </div>
        
        <p><strong>Crucial Rule:</strong> If you are borrowing an hour, you do NOT add 10 or 100 to the minutes. You must strictly add exactly <strong>60 minutes</strong> to the minute column.</p>

        <h2>Step-by-Step Explanation</h2>
        <p>To safely determine exact duration manually, especially across noon boundaries, execute this sequence perfectly:</p>
        <ol>
            <li><strong>Convert to Military Time (24h format):</strong> If crossing from AM to PM, add exactly 12 to the PM hours (e.g., 2:00 PM becomes 14:00).</li>
            <li><strong>Stack the Numbers:</strong> Write the exact End Time entirely above the exact Start Time.</li>
            <li><strong>Subtract the Minutes:</strong> Try to subtract the bottom minutes from the top. If the top minutes are absolutely smaller, borrow 1 single Hour from the hour column, and add exactly 60 Minutes to your top minute column.</li>
            <li><strong>Subtract the Hours:</strong> Subtract the heavily corrected bottom hours from the top hours.</li>
            <li><strong>Yield the Final Span:</strong> The remaining variables strictly represent the total elapsed Hours and total elapsed Minutes.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2>Real-World Example Calculation</h2>
        <p>Let's map out a real shift calculation. An employee clocks in at <strong>8:45 AM</strong>. They clock out mathematically at <strong>3:20 PM</strong>.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Step 1 (Convert to 24h):</strong> 3:20 PM becomes 15:20.</li>
            <li><strong>Step 2 (Stack):</strong><br>
                15 : 20   (End)<br>
              - 08 : 45   (Start)
            </li>
            <li><strong>Step 3 (Borrow Minutes):</strong> We cannot subtract 45 from 20. We borrow exactly 1 hour from the 15, making it 14. We add 60 minutes to the 20, making it 80.</li>
            <li><strong>Corrected Stack:</strong><br>
                14 : 80<br>
              - 08 : 45
            </li>
            <li><strong>Subtract Minutes:</strong> 80 - 45 = <strong>35 minutes</strong>.</li>
            <li><strong>Subtract Hours:</strong> 14 - 8 = <strong>6 hours</strong>.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The total exact continuous time duration for the shift is <strong>6 Hours and 35 Minutes.</strong></p>

