        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-container">
            <h3>How do I calculate duration across midnight boundaries?</h3>
            <p>If an employee works a night shift from 10:00 PM to 6:00 AM, the End Time is physically smaller than the Start Time. The easiest solution is to strictly add 24 hours to the End Time mathematically. (e.g., 6:00 AM becomes 30:00). Then simply subtract 22:00 from 30:00 to yield an 8-hour shift.</p>
            
            <h3>Why do decimal payroll times differ from clock times?</h3>
            <p>Because clocks operate on Base-60 and financial payroll operates on Base-100 (decimals). A duration of exactly 6 Hours and 30 Minutes on a clock translates entirely to 6.5 Hours on a payroll check. You must divide remaining clock minutes by 60 to find the proper decimal.</p>
            
            <h3>What is the easiest way to add massive blocks of time?</h3>
            <p>When summing up multiple spans (like 1h 45m + 2h 30m), simply add the hours completely separate from the minutes. (Total: 3h 75m). Then, since 75 minutes is larger than 60, convert 60 of those minutes into 1 hour and shift it over. Final valid answer: 4h 15m.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p>Understanding exactly how to calculate time duration protects your payroll, guarantees your scheduling structure, and eliminates messy mental fractional errors. By converting to military time, strictly borrowing 60 mathematical units instead of standard 10s, and relying heavily on automated software to crunch weekly arrays, you enforce absolute precision across all chronological accounting.</p>
